[Solution] Let there be $a, b \in S$ satisfying the condition $(a+b) \mid a b$.
Let $c=(a, b)$, then $a=c a_{1}, b=c b_{1}$, where $a_{1}, b_{1} \in \mathbb{N}$, and $\left(a_{1}, b_{1}\right)=1$. Therefore, we have $c\left(a_{1}+b_{1}\right)=(a+b) \mid a b = c^{2} a_{1} b_{1}$,
$$
\left(a_{1}+b_{1}\right) \mid c a_{1} b_{1} \text{. }
$$

Since $\left(a_{1}, b_{1}\right)=1$, it follows that $\left(a_{1}+b_{1}, a_{1}\right)=1,\left(a_{1}+b_{1}, b_{1}\right)=1$, hence $\left(a_{1}+b_{1}\right) \mid c$.
Given $a \in S, b \in S$, then $a+b \leqslant 99$, and $c\left(a_{1}+b_{1}\right) \leqslant 99$.
Thus, $3 \leqslant a_{1}+b_{1} \leqslant 9$,
From this, we know that there are 23 different pairs in $S$ that satisfy the condition $(a+b) \mid a b$:
When $a_{1}+b_{1}=3$, $(a, b)=(6,3),(12,6),(18,9),(24,12),(30,15),(36,18),(42,21),(48,24)$;
When $a_{1}+b_{1}=4$, $(a, b)=(12,4),(24,8),(36,12),(48,16)$;
When $a_{1}+b_{1}=5$, $(a, b)=(20,5),(40,10),(15,10),(30,20),(45,30)$;
