When $a_{1}+b_{1}=7$, $(a, b)=(42,7),(35,14),(28,21)$;
When $a_{1}+b_{1}=8$, $(a, b)=(40,24)$;
When $a_{1}+b_{1}=9$, $(a, b)=(45,36)$.
Let $M=\{6,12,15,18,20,21,24,35,40,42,45,48\}$, then $|M|=12$ and each of the 23 pairs above contains at least one element from $M$.

Therefore, if we let $T=S-M$, then $|T|=38$ and no two numbers in $T$ satisfy the given condition. Hence, the smallest natural number $k \geqslant 39$.
Note, the following 12 pairs that satisfy the given condition are mutually disjoint:
$(6,3),(12,4),(20,5),(42,7),(24,8),(18,9),(40,10),(35,14),(30,15),(48,16),(28,21),(45,36)$.

For any 39-element subset $R$ of $S$, it is only 11 elements less than $S$, and these 11 elements belong to at least 11 of the above 12 pairs, thus there must be one of the 12 pairs that belongs to $R$.
In summary, the smallest natural number $k=39$.

